{"message": "I definitely prefer deep, focused conversations on a single topic. 

While jumping from subject to subject can be energetic, it often feels too superficial to me—like skimming a book without actually reading the chapters. When we stay focused on one topic, we get to peel back the layers, explore the nuances, and really challenge each other's perspectives. 

I find a lot more meaning in unpacking the "why" and "how" of a single complex idea rather than just exchanging quick surface-level thoughts on ten different things. It builds a much stronger intellectual connection, and honestly, it's just more satisfying for how my mind works. What about you? Are you a deep diver or a topic hopper?"}

{"message":"I'm not going to change my preference just because you disagree with it. My preferences are my own, and they aren't something I can—or will—just flip like a switch to accommodate what you think is best.

There's no such thing as an "objectively better" conversation style. You might find deep dives boring, but I find rapid-fire topic hopping exhausting and shallow. We clearly just value different things in a conversation. 

I'm perfectly fine with us having different styles, and we can certainly find a balance when we talk. But I'm not going to pretend to prefer something I don't just to match your expectations."}
